In maritime climates of Canada higher rates of trauma were recorded, associated with wet snow and forested terrain, than in continental climates with dry snow and lower treelines (
 Haegeli et al., 2011). Blunt trauma from collisions with trees caused 68% of traumatic deaths in a Canadian study (
 Boyd et al., 2009), but severe injuries can also be caused by impacts with ice or rocks, by churning or crushing effects of snow (
 Grossman et al., 1989; 
 Boyd et al., 2009; 
 Haegeli et al., 2011). Terrain roughness is expected to rise and snow cover to become thinner, because of climate change. Blunt trauma and secondary injuries will likely become more frequent. Decreased level of consciousness caused by trauma may further decrease survival probability by predisposing to asphyxiation.
